    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-03-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-03-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="206"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d206">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115C49/8</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Glasgow</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MoCunn</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Glasgow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1917-03-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">undated</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 20, 1917, 5
                        p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Captain <persName>Borum</persName> with eight members of crew of <hi
                        rend="italic">City of Memphis</hi> arrived Glasgow, 20th. Captain reports
                        <hi rend="italic">City of Memphis</hi> was <pb facs="0354" n="182"
                        xml:id="pg_182"/> sunk 4 p.m., March 17, by German submarine 44 miles off
                    Irish coast. No resistance offered; captain ordered to abandon ship immediately.
                    Warned by two shots, across bow, four boats were launched with difficulty in
                    rough sea taking off all crew. Ship was subsequently sunk by gunfire, no other
                    steamers in sight. No assistance offered crew by submarine. Eighteen hours in
                    open boat before rescue. Ship was bound from Cardiff to New York in ballast,
                    total crew 58 including 30 Americans. Remainder crew reported landed Ireland.
                    Names crew landed Glasgow: <persName>H. O. Bevill</persName>, <persName>N. P.
                        Clausen</persName>, <persName>Charles Walker</persName>, <persName>David
                        Jackson</persName>, <persName>Fred Prutting</persName>, <persName>S.
                        Ludvigsen</persName>, <persName>Manuel Lopez</persName>, <persName>Manuel
                        Barbrito</persName>; no casualties reported here, full affidavit taken,
                    Embassy advised.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">McCunn</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
